<title>2013 Speakers</title>

<section id="janet_swisher">
  <title>Janet Swisher</title>

  <media src="janetswisher.jpg" width="160" height="156" style="floatend">
    <p>Janet Swisher</p>
  </media>

  <p>Janet Swisher Janet Swisher helps build Mozilla’s communities
  around developer documentation and technical evangelism. She has
  worked as a technical writer since 1999, and has worked on open
  source documentation since 2004. She has volunteered since 2008
  with the <link href="http://en.flossmanuals.net/">FLOSS Manuals</link>
  project. She writes about technical communication and open source
  software on her blog,
  <link href="http://www.janetswisher.com/">A Techie Technical Writer</link>.</p>

  <list style="compact">
    <item><p><link xref="sessions#janet_swisher"/></p></item>
  </list>
</section>

<section id="jorge_castro">
  <title>Jorge Castro</title>

  <media src="jorgecastro.jpg" width="160" height="160" style="floatend">
    <p>Jorge Castro</p>
  </media>

  <p>Jorge O. Castro currently works on the Community Team as Cloud
  Community Liaison for Canonical Ltd, sponsors of the Ubuntu project.
  Jorge has been using Linux since 1998, and his current passion is
  juju, the new cloud deployment tool. He has spoken at the Ohio Linux
  Fest, SCaLE, OSCON, as well as various LUGs over the years.</p>

  <list style="compact">
    <item><p><link xref="sessions#jorge_castro"/></p></item>
    <item><p><link xref="sessions#support"/></p></item>
  </list>
</section>

<section id="rich_bowen">
  <title>Rich Bowen</title>

  <media src="richbowen.jpg" width="160" height="160" style="floatend">
    <p>Rich Bowen</p>
  </media>

  <p>Rich is the OpenStack Community Liaison at Red Hat, and is also
  a 15-year veteran of Open Source documentation, on various projects
  including Apache httpd, Perl, PHP, and several others you’ve probably
  never heard of. Rich is the author of Apache Cookbook, and The
  Definitive Guide to Apache mod_rewrite.</p>

  <list style="compact">
    <item><p><link xref="sessions#rich_bowen"/></p></item>
  </list>
</section>

<section id="noirin_plunkett">
  <title>Nóirín Plunkett</title>

  <media src="nóirínplunkett.jpg" width="160" height="160" style="floatend">
    <p>Nóirín Plunkett</p>
  </media>

  <p>Nóirín Plunkett is a jack of all trades, and a master of several.
  She works for Eucalyptus Systems, as a geek&lt;->English translator,
  and general force multiplier. She’s passionate about community,
  communication, and collaboration.</p>

  <p>Her open source work epitomizes the saying “if you want something
  done, ask a busy person”: Nóirín cut her teeth on the httpd documentation
  project at Apache, and continues to contribute to projects as diverse
  as Infrastructure and Incubator. Offline, Nóirín is a keen swing dancer
  and storyteller.</p>

  <list style="compact">
    <item><p><link xref="sessions#noirin_plunkett"/></p></item>
  </list>
</section>

<section id="lee_hunter">
  <title>Lee Hunter</title>

  <media src="leehunter.jpg" width="133" height="160" style="floatend">
    <p>Lee Hunter</p>
  </media>

  <p>Lee Hunter has been contributing to the Drupal documentation for
  the past six years. One of his major goals as the newly-appointed
  Doc Team Lead is to see Drupal develop into a useful CMS for
  web-based technical communication. He’s been a writer and editor
  for more than thirty years and has worked as a technical editor
  for a number of software products including the Adobe Acrobat SDK.
  He’s also done enterprise architecture and documentation for large
  enterprise applications.</p>

  <list style="compact">
    <item><p><link xref="sessions#lee_hunter"/></p></item>
  </list>
</section>

<section id="michael_verdi">
  <title>Michael Verdi</title>

  <media src="michaelverdi.jpg" width="160" height="160" style="floatend">
    <title>Michael Verdi</title>
  </media>

  <p>Michael Verdi joined the Mozilla support team in 2010 as the
  content manager. In addition to creating Firefox documentation
  and screencasts seen by millions, he works on ways to keep people
  from ever having to visit the support site to begin with. He
  occasionally blogs about this at
  <link href="https://blog.mozilla.org/verdi">https://blog.mozilla.org/verdi</link>.</p>

  <list style="compact">
